  "prompt": "What are all time best movies to watch?",
  "response": "Choosing the \"best\" movies can be highly subjective, but several films are widely regarded as classics or must-sees across various genres. Here are some all-time great movies that often feature on top lists:\n\n### Classics\n1. **Citizen Kane** (1941) - Directed by Orson Welles, often cited as one of the greatest films ever made.\n2. **Casablanca** (1942) - A romantic drama set during World War II starring Humphrey Bogart and Ingrid Bergman.\n3. **Gone with the Wind** (1939) - An epic historical romance about love and loss during the American Civil War.\n\n### Drama\n4. **The Godfather** (1972) - A powerful story of family and organized crime directed by Francis Ford Coppola.\n5. **Schindler's List** (1993) - Steven Spielberg's harrowing portrayal of the Holocaust and one man's effort to save Jews.\n6. **Forrest Gump** (1994) - A tale of an extraordinary man living through pivotal moments in American history.\n\n### Action/Adventure\n7. **Pulp Fiction** (1994) - Quentin Tarantino's influential crime film with intertwining stories.\n8. **The Dark Knight** (2008) - Christopher Nolan's critically acclaimed superhero film featuring Heath Ledger's Joker.\n9. **Raiders of the Lost Ark** (1981) - An action-packed adventure featuring Indiana Jones, directed by Steven Spielberg.\n\n### Science Fiction/Fantasy\n10. **2001: A Space Odyssey** (1968) - Stanley Kubrick's visually stunning exploration of space and humanity.\n11. **Star Wars: Episode IV - A New Hope** (1977) - George Lucas's groundbreaking space opera that launched a beloved franchise.\n12. **The Matrix** (1999) - A mind-bending sci-fi film that explores reality and consciousness.\n\n### Animation\n13. **Spirited Away** (2001) - Hayao Miyazaki's enchanting and imaginative animated film from Studio Ghibli.\n14. **Toy Story** (1995) - The first feature-length film made entirely with computer animation, beloved by all ages.\n\n### Comedy\n15. **Some Like It Hot** (1959) - A classic comedy featuring Jack Lemmon and Tony Curtis in an unforgettable plot.\n16. **Monty Python and the Holy Grail** (1975) - A parody of the Arthurian legend filled with absurd humor.\n\n### Horror\n17. **Psycho** (1960) - Alfred Hitchcock's suspenseful thriller and a milestone in the horror genre.\n18. **The Exorcist** (1973) - A terrifying tale of demonic possession that redefined horror movies.\n\n### Recent Acclaimed Films\n19. **Parasite** (2019) - Bong Joon-ho\u2019s genre-blending social commentary that won the Academy Award for Best Picture.\n20. **Everything Everywhere All at Once** (2022) - A unique multiverse adventure exploring themes of family and identity.\n\nThese films span a range of genres and styles, offering something for everyone. Depending on your preferences, there are many other films that could also be considered among the best.",
